The ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' [[Film franchise|franchise]] is a [[Fantasy film|fantasy]]-[[Adventure film|adventure]] film series consisting of ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'' (2003), ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest|Dead Man's Chest]]'' (2006), ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End|At World's End]]'' (2007), ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides|On Stranger Tides]]'' (2011), and ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales|Dead Men Tell No Tales]]'' (2017). The first three films were directed by [[Gore Verbinski]], while the fourth was by [[Rob Marshall]], the series was written by [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] and [[Terry Rossio]], produced by [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and distributed by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The ''Pirates'' films have featured such characters as [[Jack Sparrow|Captain Jack Sparrow]] ([[Johnny Depp]]), [[Will Turner]] ([[Orlando Bloom]]), [[Elizabeth Swann]] ([[Keira Knightley]]), [[Hector Barbossa|Captain Hector Barbossa]] ([[Geoffrey Rush]]), [[Joshamee Gibbs]] ([[Kevin McNally]]), [[Davy Jones (Pirates of the Caribbean)|Davy Jones]] ([[Bill Nighy]]), Angelica ([[Penélope Cruz]]), [[Blackbeard]] ([[Ian McShane]]), Philip Swift ([[Sam Claflin]]) and Syrena ([[Àstrid Bergès-Frisbey]]). [[Hans Zimmer]] composed the score primarily, although [[Klaus Badelt]] composed for the first film.

''The Curse of the Black Pearl'' was 2003's fourth highest-grossing film worldwide (behind ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'', ''[[Finding Nemo]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'').<ref name="gross">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2003&p=.htm|title=2003 Worldwide Grosses|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref> ''Dead Man's Chest'' was 2006's highest-grossing film worldwide,<ref name="gross2">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2006&p=.htm|title=2006 Worldwide Grosses|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref> and the [[List of highest-grossing films|sixth highest-grossing film of all time]] (originally third), behind ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'', ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'', ''[[Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 2]]'', ''[[Transformers: Dark of the Moon]]'' and ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]''. ''At World's End'' was 2007's highest-grossing film worldwide and the twelfth highest ever (originally sixth),<ref name="gross3">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2007&p=.htm|title=2007 Worldwide Grosses|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref> and ''On Stranger Tides'' was [[2011 in film|2011's third highest-grossing film of 2011]] and is the [[List of highest-grossing films|twelfth highest-grossing film of all time worldwide]].<ref name="gross4">{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-report-pirates-caribbean-195646|title=Box Office Report: 'Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides' Sails Past $800 Million Globally|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=June 18, 2011|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|date=June 7, 2011}}</ref>

The ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' films have received a generally mixed-to-positive response. ''The Curse of the Black Pearl'' received critical acclaim, with 79% positive reviews of 197 sampled critics on [[Review aggregator|review aggregate]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and garnered an average rating of 7.1/10.<ref name="tom1">{{cite web |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl Movie Reviews |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_the_curse_of_the_black_pearl |accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref> ''Dead Man's Chest'' received a mixed-to-positive reception, with a 54% "Rotten" rating on Rotten Tomatoes.<ref name="deadmc">{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_dead_mans_chest | title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest (2006) | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref> ''At World's End'' has a "Rotten" rating of 45% on Rotten Tomatoes<ref name="toms3">[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_3 "Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Movie Reviews, Pictures"]. Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved June 18, 2011.</ref> and 50% at [[Metacritic]],<ref name="meta">[http://www.metacritic.com/movie/piratesofthecaribbeanatworldsend "Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End Reviews, Ratings, Credits"]. ''[[Metacritic]]''. Retrieved June 18, 2011.</ref> although opinions differed from positive<ref>{{cite news |author=Alex Billington |title=Get Ready for a Swarm of Negative Critics This Friday on Pirates 3 |publisher=''FirstShowing.net'' |date=May 22, 2007 |url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2007/05/22/get-ready-for-a-swarm-of-negative-critics-this-friday-on-pirates-3 |accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=[[Drew McWeeny]] |title=Moriarty Sets Sail With PIRATES 3: AT WORLD’S END! |publisher=''[[Ain't It Cool News]]'' |date=May 24, 2007 |url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/32783 |accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref> to negative.<ref name="totalfilms">{{cite news |title=Pirates Of The Caribbean: At World's End |publisher=''[[Total Film]]'' |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/cinema_reviews/films_out_this_week/pirates_of_the_caribbean_at_worlds_end |accessdate=2009-05-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070524075651/http://www.totalfilm.com/cinema_reviews/films_out_this_week/pirates_of_the_caribbean_at_worlds_end |archivedate=May 24, 2007 }}</ref><ref name="reel">{{cite news |author=[[James Berardinelli]] |title=Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End |publisher=''Reelviews'' |year=2007 |url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/p/pirates_caribbean3.html |accessdate=June 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.iomtoday.co.im/reviews?articleid=2938064 "Review by Colm Andrew"]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. ''IOM Today''. Retrieved June 18, 2011.</ref> Like its predecessors, ''On Stranger Tides'' has received generally mixed reviews. Rotten Tomatoes reports that 33% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 232 reviews, with an average score of 5/10.<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_on_stranger_tides "Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides Movie Reviews"]. [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. Retrieved June 18, 2011.</ref> ''Dead Men Tell No Tales'' continued this trend as it also received a mixed reception, garnering a 30% "Rotten" rating on Rotten Tomatoes, with an average rating of 4.9/10.<ref>{{Citation|title=Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/pirates_of_the_caribbean_dead_men_tell_no_tales/|language=en|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref>

It has won a plethora of prestigious awards and has gathered 10 [[Academy Award]] nominations (five for ''The Curse of the Black Pearl'', three for ''Dead Man's Chest'' and two for ''At World's End''),<ref name="academynoms1" /><ref name="oscars2" /><ref name="oscars3" /> with one win for [[Academy Award for Best Visual Effects|Best Visual Effects]] in 2006 for ''Dead Man's Chest''.<ref name="oscars2" /> ''Pirates'' has also won two BAFTA awards,<ref name="bafta1" /><ref name="bafta2" /><ref name="bafta3" /> 17 [[Teen Choice Awards]],<ref name="teen" /><ref name="teenc" /> and has been nominated for two [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globes]],<ref name="golden" /><ref name="golden2" /> two [[American Cinema Editors|Eddie awards]] (winning one),<ref name="vari" /><ref name="var2" /><ref name="var3" /> one [[Grammy Awards|Grammy]],<ref name="grams" /> nine [[MTV Movie Awards]] (winning four),<ref name="mtv1" /><ref name="mtv2" /><ref name="mtv3" /> 17 [[Saturn Awards]] (winning four),<ref name="sat30" /><ref name="sat33" /><ref name="sat34" /> seven [[Satellite Awards|Satellites]] (winning one)<ref name="satellite" /> and two [[Artios Awards]].<ref name="artiosf" /><ref name="artiosg" />

==''The Curse of the Black Pearl''==
[[File:KeiraKnightleyByAndreaRaffin2011 (cropped).jpg|thumb|175px|[[Keira Knightley]] was nominated for two [[Saturn Award]]s for her portrayal of [[Elizabeth Swann]]<ref name="sat30" />]]

The franchise's first film, ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'', was released in 2003 to a high gross,<ref name="gross" /> and positive reviews,<ref name="tom1" /> with ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine claiming it to be "the best blockbuster of the summer"<ref>{{cite news |author=Alan Morrison |title=Pirates Of The Caribbean: The Curse Of The Black Pearl |work=''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' |url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=9271 |accessdate=June 19, 2011}}</ref> and [[Roger Ebert]] praising [[Johnny Depp]]'s performance for its "originality".<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Roger Ebert]] |title=Pirates Of The Caribbean: The Curse Of The Black Pearl :: rogerebert.com :: Reviews |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 9, 2003 |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20030709/REVIEWS/307090301/1023 |accessdate=June 19, 2011}}</ref> It was directed by [[Gore Verbinski]] and produced by [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]. The story is of a blacksmith, [[Will Turner]], ([[Orlando Bloom]]) and a pirate, Captain [[Jack Sparrow]] ([[Johnny Depp]]), as they rescue a kidnapped [[Elizabeth Swann]] ([[Keira Knightley]]) from the cursed crew of the ''[[Black Pearl]]'', captained by [[Hector Barbossa]] ([[Geoffrey Rush]]).

It was nominated for five Academy Awards, but did not win in any of its categories.<ref name="academynoms1" /><ref name="blackfix" /> It was also nominated for five [[BAFTA Awards]] (winning one),<ref name="bafta1" /> five [[Empire Awards]] (winning one),<ref name="emp1" /><ref name="emp2" /><ref name="emp3" /><ref name="emp4" /><ref name="emp5" /> one [[Golden Globe]],<ref name="golden" /> three [[Motion Picture Sound Editors|Golden Reel Awards]] (winning one),<ref name="motio" /> six [[MTV Movie Awards]] (winning one),<ref name="mtv1" /> five [[Online Film Critics Society Awards]],<ref name="ofcsa" /> eight Phoenix Film Critics Society Awards,<ref name="phoen" /> six [[Satellite Awards]],<ref name="satellite" /> 11 [[Saturn Awards]] (winning one),<ref name="sat30" /> five [[Teen Choice Awards]] (winning four),<ref name="teens1" /> eight [[Visual Effects Society Award]] (winning two)<ref name="teens1" /> and two [[Washington DC Area Film Critics Association Awards]] (winning one),<ref name="wash1" /><ref name="wash2" /> with multiple other awards.<ref name="stars" /><ref name="adg" />
